         <tr class=3D"replica" name=3D"s16">
          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">So=E2=80=A6 who car=
es? Movies are a business of talent and material, and studios have simply b=
ecome better at setting up pipelines for both. But producers like Beaubaire=
 would argue that studios, and especially streamers, are neglecting the <i>=
development</i> phase of the filmmaking process. <br/><br/>Studios used to =
carry dozens of on-set producers who were paid to push projects through the=
 pipeline to a greenlight, then act as quality control through to the finis=
hed product. These days, producers on the lots are rare, and there=E2=80=99=
s much less development overall. Even though a studio pipeline might contai=
n 300 to 600 projects at various stages, from active development to turnaro=
und, nearly all of those projects now simply peter out and die. <br/><br/>T=
he reality these days is the studios don=E2=80=99t have the resources or th=
e inclination to focus much on
internal development when effective franchise management and remaining comp=
etitive in bidding wars is valued most. Think about it: If you=E2=80=99re o=
verseeing $500 million worth of movies in production, plus $500 million wor=
th of movies that are set to release, you likely don=E2=80=99t have time to=
 read the third draft of some project one of your executives is developing.=
 You=E2=80=99re just gonna buy the big A-list package that=E2=80=99s sittin=
g on your desk, waiting for a yes. <br/> <br/>Like he said, Beaubaire sees =
an opening. He=E2=80=99s now positioning Sunset Lane, which has some outsid=
e backing, to take on development of original film projects that the studio=
s aren=E2=80=99t: smaller books, true stories, commercial ideas. He wants t=
o engage talent early in the process. To hustle. To reverse the thinking th=
at development is too often wasted money. =E2=80=9CDevelopment =E2=80=A6 is=
 the thing that everything relies on, but it gets the least amount of atten=
tion at a studio,=E2=80=9D he told me. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s really hard to
generate, let alone sustain, the level of enthusiasm you need for a project=
 over a long period of time within a large organization that is, by nature,=
 risk-averse.=E2=80=9D<br/> <br/>He=E2=80=99s not alone here. Companies lik=
e MRC (<i>American Fiction</i>), Fifth Season (<i>80 for Brady</i>), Artist=
s Equity (<i>Air</i>), and others are packaging projects in place of the st=
udios and selling them to the highest bidders. It can be a good business an=
d lead to better payouts for the talent involved. For the most part, though=
, these outfits are <i>financiers</i>, bringing money to the table. Beaubai=
re wants to act more like a consulting firm for creativity and development,=
 partnering with studios to shepherd projects and adding value and urgency =
to the development process, thus bringing producers back into the equation.=
    <br/> <br/>It=E2=80=99s not a bad rebranding idea for the value of prod=
ucers. Risk-aversion and the perception of a higher bar for theaters has fo=
rced the traditional studios
into a cycle of pre-branded spectacles. The goal, for now, is =E2=80=9Cfami=
liar surprise,=E2=80=9D as NBCUniversal=E2=80=99s <b>Donna Langley</b> said=
 today at a conference. But studios are so focused on extending their <i>ex=
isting</i> franchises that they neglect to develop <i>new </i>ones. As my c=
olleague <b>Scott Mendelson</b> likes to point out, Disney hasn=E2=80=99t c=
reated an original live-action movie franchise since <i>National Treasure</=
i> exactly 20 years ago, right before <b>Bob</b> <b>Iger </b>took over. <i>=
Two decades.</i> <br/><br/>As evidenced this year by original successes lik=
e <i>Anyone But You</i> and <i>Longlegs</i>, the audience for original, com=
mercial films is still there. And streaming services would benefit from, fr=
ankly, better movies, especially given what they are paying for them. If th=
e studios and streamers actually want to generate a <i>new</i> generation o=
f franchises, maybe reorienting the business around development will lead t=
o more of them.<br/></td>
         </tr>
